Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, totaling 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous large coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought after the first preliminary results the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People’s Party (<0xC3><0x96>VP) suffered particularly harsh losses, where the position of former chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the brink.
In contrast, the electoral leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZ<0xC3><0x96>), the Carinthian state chief Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SP<0xC3><0x96>) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but compared to the last elections in 2006, it loses 5.5 percent of the votes.
Even worse was the <0xC3><0x96>VP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in Austrian post-war history, and especially in the People’s Party, which had demanded the early elections, this is a really disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the <0xC3><0x96>VP had left the coalition, the People’s Party had a clear advantage over the SP<0xC3><0x96>.
The voters, however, have probably punished the party for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party’s chairmanship.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the large coalition of SP<0xC3><0x96> and <0xC3><0x96>VP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FP<0xC3><0x96>) received 18 percent for the time being, the BZ<0xC3><0x96> 11 percent of the votes - the Social Democrats expressed their fear that the year 1999 could repeat itself, when the People's Party had agreements with the populists (then the FP<0xC3><0x96> was still unified in terms of a European government, in 2005 it split from the BZ<0xC3><0x96>)
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is willing to cooperate with any party, is obviously relying on this development and assumes a return to Vienna in Austrian federal politics.
The party of the Greens also entered parliament, but suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the 4% barrier and, as a result, did not move into parliament.
