Organizers are seeing rising booking numbers
It seems to be a good winter for the German tour operators:
In the case of travel bookings for the coming months, sales have increased significantly compared to the previous year, according to a study - even by more than 30 percent for the winter season.
Despite weak economic outlook, the Germans’ travel appetite remains undisturbed, according to a study.
For bookings for the winter season, the travel agencies recorded a 31 percent increase in sales compared to the previous year's period, as the German Travel Association (DRV) announced on Monday in Berlin.
According to the study by the market research institute GfK, booking numbers have already increased for the autumn months.
For example, the sales growth of travel agencies for October was around eleven percent compared to 2007, the DRV said.
These results are based on figures from GfK, which evaluates monthly booking data from 1200 German travel agencies and calculates them for the overall market.
This includes travel bookings made until the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar exchange rate, travel to the US is particularly in demand, the DRV said.
Here, the booking growth amounts to around a third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as the local regions, are particularly sought after by the Germans.
In particular, holiday packages are high on the agenda, DRV President Klaus Laepple explained.
In view of rising costs for energy and food, the costs are "more calculable for the customer than for individually organised holidays".
Consumers could save money by, among other things, early booking discounts or all-inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months were also very well booked, so that sales will again increase compared to the previous year - although, according to another study, the number of Germans who took a trip decreased compared to the previous year.
