Turkey expands diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrating deep into the hinterland of Turkey.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps inside Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial aspiration.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the guides tell you.
The building sits riding at the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front and thus looks like some provincial German Town Hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building is about to collapse.
But once you are inside the vaulted ticket counter, there is no doubt about the grandeur of the project whose westernmost access it was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Bagdad Society.
Germany, which was a late thief in the imperialist game, had to implement before its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, Germany’s imperialist plans paralysed during the First World War.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable boundaries of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces emerged from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha train station.
In 1917, an ammunition train flew into the air, destroying the artistic roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly disintegrated, largely ignored from history.
Nowadays, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and everything east of it, highlighting the expansion of the diplomatic horizon of Tukei.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the neighboring regions, generated by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of approximation.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian splinter groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the key elements of this new foreign policy, I took the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the same old-world footsteps in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is regarded as a new city for the new secular state project of turning its back on the Ottoman past.
The AKP, however, which is known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity.
This has sparked some mistrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a custom-made, ultra-modern stone and steel structure, in a developing suburb, surrounded by semi-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to complete the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician of almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception," he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays, she has to look east and west at the same time.
There would be no one or the other.
She would have to do both.
"But certainly Turkey could at some point," I asked, "be forced to make a decision?"
“Turkey,” he said, “wouldn’t have to face this decision.”
He then highlighted a point that almost everyone with whom I spoke here almost routinely abandoned: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial for Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, can, in a figurative sense, Europe as a whole on those same railroad tracks head east towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha’s station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German lords, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, be in the hands of Turkey.
And as I waited at the jetty for the ferry that was going to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called “the sick man of Europe” in those days.
At that time, at least, there seemed to be little doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Dead" Handley (officially on September 11th) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his magnificent youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for young people up to 21 years old, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979, some of us were already in the late 20s - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological shape changer) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to tackle any piece of music presented to him, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting and existed only thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for the music that never faded for years.
How often did death keep us from “letting the music speak for itself.”
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in the music.
So sing it!"
His way of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never dominant but never exuberant.
No matter how high the musical level was, he always demanded an even higher level.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been beaten to knight, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, when he led the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the last 40 years or so, I’ve written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts and I can honestly say that I’ve never been disappointed by a single one – often I was inspired by them.
Tod Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He detested conductors who, according to his words, simply "went to house with one or two well-known shovel horses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (September 25), you write that "he resumed teaching economic history in Oxford in 1946 and received a Houblon-Norman research scholarship in 1950 ... while at the same time studying for a BSc, an MA and a doctorate.
This is a conclusion from an author's remark in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End", but it is not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He spent 1950-1951 in the United States in the course of a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953, he finally left Nottingham and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
