"Auto-bee" that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature, more precisely, by bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight is based on the swarm behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a bio-mimetic car robot drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accident prevention technologies.
The engineers from Nissan Motor Co.’s technical development center developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the prestigious University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan Safety Shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped aerospace, which is very similar to the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important are the facet eyes of the bee, which can see at an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows it to fly undisturbed in its personal airspace without interruption.
To replicate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It detects obstacles that are up to two meters away from the BR23C and are in a 180 degree radius, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor, which is translated directly into signal to avoid collision.
At the moment when an obstacle is noticed, the small robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at 90o or even greater angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to other arbitrary systems is that this evasive maneuver takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it were not, the robot might not be able to respond with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Laboratory for Mobility and the senior engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate either upwards or downwards, but also not overhead; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways, as the bees do.
For this reason, in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions, Nissan has used the rotation function so that the small robot avoids the collisions.
This device only takes a few seconds to process the information and act accordingly.
It does not require the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers carried out to be stored, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it’s not about the GBs and not even the MBs of the storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for immediate collision prevention, a technology Nissan predicts to introduce to production cars over the next ten years.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to guide to the destination while driving, while avoiding the obstacles on the way.
