Morgan Stanley makes its capital available for MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, making it the first bank in Japan to spend $9 billion and take over 21% of its capital, an innovation attributable to a sharp fall in its stock market price.
A week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks stated that MUFG will buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley stock at a uniform price of $25.25, resulting in a total of $3 billion.
The assumed price is below 19% of the price of the share as of August 31.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible shares, which will secure a 10% profit and will be resold at a price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global business will be done on the basis of a uniform average price of $29, which is 28% above the current price.
However, the Morgan Stanley share fell by 6.79% to $23.07 at 17.00 GMT.
“This strategic link represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to holding bank status,” said John Mack, director-general of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this status last week, which should allow it to expand its operations to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest names to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The arrangements presented on Monday also show that the deal has changed over the last few days: Last Monday, Morgan had simply stated that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” Tokyo’s Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of the MUFG, said, “we thought that the stake would be made up entirely of ordinary shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and hedge ourselves.”
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay their Morgan Stanley shares 7% below their price value.
And the business will go with a reduction in profits by about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into ordinary shares in one year if the latter are exchanged within a given period to more than 50% above the value of the sale, i.e. to approximately $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will allow it to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its sales.
However, a spokesman for the group refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should be able to post a payability ratio of approximately 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan said that his balance sheet had been “definitely lowered” since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been tough for the group, which had to watch as their stock market price fell by half, while the price of insolvency insurance rose rapidly.
This price went down on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only “survivor” of Wall Street’s major investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that it had withdrawn $15 billion from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Re-establishing the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorialist Rafael Correa.
It was that third party who, following the example of his like-minded and friends, presented this Sunday the plan for a new constitution.
According to the public results of 80% of the voters, 64% voted "yes" in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% of the ballots were invalid, and 0.7% were left empty.
In order for the constitutional project to be approved, one vote must be obtained more than half of all votes cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization announced a clear victory for “yes,” predicting it from 63% to 70%.
In the night from Sunday to Monday, Rafael Correa had, by the way, called for the victory of his constitutional project.
The “Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly,” he had assured in Guayaquil, the seat of government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorians.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held silently in accordance with the OAS Observation Delegation, referred to a 444-point text to secure the “new socialism” for which the president is advocating.
The constitutional project transfers state power to the economy by giving it the sole right to “development planning” in a country that lives largely from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and from the foreign exchange that sends immigrants to the country.
The project, driven by the Correa elected in 2006, also grants the head of state more extensive power, who will be able to exercise up to two consecutive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will make use of this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also secures the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population live below the poverty line.
Ultimately, it also intends to ban the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Equatorial base as a base for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad.
An Egyptian command launched the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions, who had been captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held captive in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital healthy and unharmed this Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were liberated by an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages reached the al-Maza military base right next to the Cairo International Airport at about 3:30 p.m. on board a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to speak to the press, aboard a helicopter to the hospital of Maadi, a foreign district of Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy “best health” and the kidnappers “were not paid a ransom,” Egypt’s tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said on the runway.
After being captured at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya on September 19, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken from one hiding place by 35 unknown kidnappers.
There are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said that 30 members of the special forces, from aboard two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
"Shots were fired on both sides and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled," he said.
He explained that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomats Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade where he is currently, on the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and performance of our men from the intelligence and special forces," he explained without further details.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the eve, the Sudanese army claimed to have stopped a patrol vehicle in which the kidnappers were found, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and detaining two.
The army stated that they were connected to a rebel group from Darfour, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U) movement, which it immediately denied.
