Benelux governments nationalized parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalisation, the Benelux countries want to help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis Bank, which is in turmoil due to the US financial crisis: The three countries make a total of EUR 11.2 billion available to the banking and insurance institute, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands discussed this weekend at the highest level, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commission’s Commissioner for Competition.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial market crisis that has been going on for a year, so decisions now taken in connection with the bank could have precedent.
In line with the decision made on Sunday night, all three states buy the respective shares of the bank at about 49 percent.
The bank is likely to sell some of its holdings, most notably the insurance activities purchased by the Dutch ABN Amro last year.
The shares of Fortis started a steep descent last week, with serious crisis scenarios already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank with its 85,000 employees is far too big for a bankruptcy.
The Institute’s securities fell by 12% on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of the shares has declined by more than two thirds.
In view of the current share prices, the Group’s market value amounts to EUR 14 billion, but this is unrealistic, according to management.
According to management, the $700 billion US bailout and the resulting market uncertainty is to blame for the downturn in Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, the prices increased slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed the Bank’s new Director-General.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but it has not found any interested person with a factual offer.
The Belgian government, however, was trying to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, it said.
There has been no panic among the customers so far, the bank's branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but it also calls leasing companies its own.
Fox in the chicken coop
Due to a person’s drug use, in America life and health insurance often refuses to enter into a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of the drug data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens" - quotes the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurance companies determine the fees and payment amounts in the event of damage depending on the health condition of the customer, and should the risk be assessed too high, the insurance is not taken out at all.
In the past, the customer was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the examination results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: based on the identification number of the customer, he obtained the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, i.e., which preparations were purchased, and the program calculated from what disease the customer suffers and what his health condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it could be concluded that his blood fat levels are untreatablely high, which would automatically place him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many medications can be taken for various purposes, such as for migraines and hot flashes, but also for depression.
From the point of view of insurers, the latter is a high-risk factor, while those mentioned before do not.
For the query and processing of the data, separate companies have been formed, which, before obtaining the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and link them to data on drug use, providing an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, and controlling their use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to healthcare providers and insurance companies.
The bill had already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is too little, so he wants to further develop his program so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the person concerned may hardly be able to prohibit access to his data, since the insurance companies do not otherwise conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are left to the fox's mercy.
