Billionaire Steve Fossett's small plane disappeared a year ago
Steve Fossett's small plane, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007, was found.
The items have been found on a 3000-metre high plateau, in the area of the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the aircraft.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, fully dispelled the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located, whereupon a troop was dispatched. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane Steve Fossett was flying with on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found in the plane or its proximity.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Department of Transportation (Ntsb) announced that just hours after the plane was sighted, a crew was dispatched to identify the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett took off in Yerington, Nevada on a 3-hour flight.
Yesterday, some of Fossett’s personal belongings were finally found in California, near the border with Nevada, by a couple near their home on the Mammoth Lakes.
These are two identification cards called Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after its disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history through a long series of records.
In 2002, in his sixth run, he became the first person to circle the world ball in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single flight without a stopover on an airplane.
Among his several records also includes an altitude flight of 15445 m above the Andes, but this one with a co-pilot.
